Bombardment in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of President Barack Obama's main assets.
Yet it seems today that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After saying last March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react strongly to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself entangled with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
US Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of gas "moral obscenity."
But torturing children, which was a precursor to the civil war two years ago, is just as obscene.
And is killing civilians with chemical products any more morally obscene than bombing them, shooting at them, or letting them starve to death?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that certain weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, particularly nuclear bombs, certainly cause more damage and faster than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in just one night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, argues that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and revert to "more mundane means for massacring his people."
In my opinion, it makes no sense.
The issue is surely that of the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral outrage, however justified, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese people in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with US support.
Is this therefore a legal issue? The use of chemical weapons constitutes a factual violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), which, incidentally, was established by a treaty that the US has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not easily defensible policy.
One could however argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the US as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are mass murdered?
Tolerating genocide is not acceptable.
But where exactly should one draw the line?
How many murders constitute genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or does the number not matter?
After all, genocide is about intent; there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic background, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before military intervention in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to it means asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the ICC's actions, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a great power.
No one would consider launching missiles at China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or enforcing international norms and standards related to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is also not a great power.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries such as Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There can be no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that American intervention would reduce the risk of a broader conflict.
In fact, some proponents of American intervention – both neoconservatives and “liberal hawks” – seem to want the opposite: they call for war with Iran.
And Obama probably drew a link in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, can we expect from American strikes on Syrian targets when Obama has already indicated that they are not aimed at bringing down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But one missile would be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, sparking a surge in violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And from a majority of Americans.
This might even be Obama's view, which is why he desperately tries to gain time by delegating to the US Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relationships with Congress have not been easy.
But he needs it more than ever now to cover his bases.
